The paper focuses on developing a fast non-invasive diagnostic tool for obstructive sleep apnea using facial images. This involves training a classifier using both persistent homology and geometric shape analysis from the field of computational topology, as well as convolutional neural networks from deep learning. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition). The paper also involves machine learning techniques such as deep learning, which suggests it could also belong to cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). Additionally, the paper involves human-computer interaction (HCI) as it aims to develop a tool for diagnosing a medical condition, which suggests it could belong to cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction). Finally, the paper involves image processing, which suggests it could also belong to cs.MM (Multimedia).
